{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LzU8wezWbUDtMKwV2gcHWT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The test has `WORD ONE` followed by `INGREDIENTS`. My change allows merging when `wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4`. `INGREDIENTS` is 1 word, `WORD ONE` is 2 words, so it merges — which is wrong for this case.\n\nThe task wants `LEMON HERB ROASTED` + `VEGETABLES` to merge, but not `WORD ONE` + `INGREDIENTS`.\n\nThe difference is that `INGREDIENTS` is a high-confidence section label (it's a standard English word that clearly demarcates a section), while `VEGETABLES` is being used as part of a title.\n\n\nI'm realizing both cases have the same structure: a 2-4 word prefix followed by a single-word label. The real distinction might be whether the single word is a structural section marker like `INGREDIENTS` versus a category word like `VEGETABLES` that belongs in a title. I should probably define a specific set of ingredient category words that are safe to merge with preceding fragments. I need to reconcile the task requirements with the existing test constraints. The task wants me to allow merging for single-word section labels when the preceding text is 2-4 words, but the `WORD ONE INGREDIENTS` test expects no merge. I think the distinction is that certain labels like `INGREDIENTS`, `DIRECTIONS`, and `METHOD` are strong structural markers that should never merge, while more ambiguous labels like `VEGETABLES` could be food categories that might appear in titles. So I need a hybrid approach that treats these strong section labels as non-mergeable while applying the relaxed rules to other single-word labels.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":931,"cache_read_input_tokens":25542,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":931},"output_tokens":8,"s