{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LPzWZP5Xc4DZ2cAuw4CvQW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the structure. The SECTION_LABELS has:\n1. Process/structural labels (ingredients, directions, instructions, method, etc.) — these should always block merges\n2. Food category/chapter labels (vegetables, fish, soups, etc.) — these could be part of titles\n\nI'll add a `STRUCTURAL_SECTION_LABELS` set containing just the process/structural ones, and use that to check if a single-word label should still block the merge.\n\nThe condition becomes:\n- Allow merge if: not a section label at all\n- OR: it's a section label but it's a food category (not structural), AND the preceding fragment is short (2-4 words)\n\n\nI'm thinking through whether to define the structural labels separately or instead create a set of just the food category labels and check against that for the merge relaxation. The category approach seems cleaner since I only need to list the ones where merging is allowed.\n\nDefining category labels... Refining the merge logic...\n\nThe approach is cleaner because it separates structural labels from category labels, preventing unwanted merges like `INGREDIENTS` while still allowing category-specific ones like `VEGETABLES` to combine when appropriate.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2828,"cache_read_input_tokens":30559,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2828},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6746208e-9db7-45b5-89d0-a33b9f6b28a6","uuid":"61201f69-a987-4593-9198-8e0c78d79d9d"}
